\begin_layout Description
Problem 3.1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obviously, since 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Wx$
\end_inset

 is also a vector, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\, vector\, x,\,||x||_{W}=||Wx||\geq0$
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0,\,||x||_{W}=||Wx||=0$
\end_inset

.
 And if 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||_{W}=||Wx||=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Wx=0$
\end_inset

 by the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $||\centerdot||$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary nonsingular matrix, which means all of row vectors are linear
 indenpendent, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||_{W}=0$
\end_inset

 if only and if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\forall\, vector\, x\: and\, y,\,||x+y||_{W}=||W(x+y)||=||Wx+Wy||\leq||Wx||+||Wy||=||x||_{W}+||y||_{W}$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Thirdly, for any scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $||\alpha x||_{W}=||W(\alpha x)||=||\alpha Wx||=\alpha||Wx||=\alpha||x||_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $||\centerdot||_{W}$
\end_inset

 is vector norm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Problem 3.2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 denote arbitrary eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding eigenvector, then we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ax=\lambda x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
get norm of both sides, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
||Ax||=||\lambda x||=|\lambda|||x||
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the definition of induced matrix norm
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
||A||=sup_{x\neq0}\frac{||Ax||}{||x||}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\lambda|\,||x||=||Ax||\leq||A||\,||x||
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $|\lambda|\leq||A||$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)\leq||A||$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Problem 3.6
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obviously, for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||'=sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}x|\geq0$
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0,\,||x||'=sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}0|=0$
\end_inset

.
 And when 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $||x||'=sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}x|=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}x|=sup_{||y||=1}||x||\,||y||\,|\cos(\theta)|
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\theta)=\frac{y^{*}x}{||x||\,||y||}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $0=sup_{||y||=1}||x||\,||y||\,|\cos(\theta)|=||x||$
\end_inset

, (because 
\begin_inset Formula $||y||=1$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $sup\cos(\theta)=1$
\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||'=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, for any two vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $||x+z||'=sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}(x+z)|=sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}x+y^{*}z|\leq sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}x|+sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}z|=||x||'+||z||'$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Thirdly, for any scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $||\alpha x||'=sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}(\alpha x)|=|\alpha|\, sup_{||y||=1}|y^{*}x|=|\alpha|\,||x||'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $||\centerdot||'$
\end_inset

 is a norm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(b).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x,\, y$
\end_inset

 is give with 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||=||y||=1,$
\end_inset

 then to show there exits a rank one 
\begin_inset Formula $B=yz^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Bx=y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $||B||=1$
\end_inset

is to show there is such a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Bx=y\,\Longleftrightarrow\, Bx-y=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $||Bx-y||=0=||yz^{*}x-y||=||y(z^{*}x-1)||$
\end_inset

 sinc e 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}x$
\end_inset

 is scalar here, and 
\begin_inset Formula $||y||=1$
\end_inset

 by given, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|z^{*}x-1|=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the lemma, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, there exits a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $|z^{*}x|=||z||'||x||$
\end_inset

, then for the given 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{|z^{*}x|}{||z||'}-1=0$
\end_inset

, to get rid of the absolute value sign, we let
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{o}=sign(z^{*}x)\frac{z}{||z||'}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then this 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $z_{o}$
\end_inset

 statisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $Bx=y$
\end_inset

, and it is easy verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $||B||=\underset{||x||=1}{sup}||Bx||=\underset{||x||=1}{sup}||y||=1$
\end_inset

.
 Besides, since both 
\begin_inset Formula $y,\, z_{o}\in\mathbb{C}^{m}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $B=yz_{o}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is always a rank-one matrix, because all the row vectors of the matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are linear dependent, i.e.
 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j,\,1\leq i,\, j\leq m$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\overrightarrow{b_{i}}}{\overrightarrow{b_{j}}}=\frac{y_{i}}{y_{i}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{b_{i}}\overrightarrow{,\, b_{i}}$
\end_inset

 are two distinct row vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i},\, y_{j}$
\end_inset

 are the corresponding entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Problem 5.3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solotion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-2 & 11\\
-10 & 5
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, then we denot 
\begin_inset Formula $M\triangleq A^{*}A$
\end_inset

, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-2 & -10\\
11 & 5
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-2 & 11\\
-10 & 5
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
104 & -72\\
-72 & 146
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
it is easy to compute the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\,\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $|M-\lambda I|=0\Rightarrow(\lambda_{1}-200)(\lambda_{2}-50)=0$
\end_inset

, thus 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=200>\lambda_{2}=50$
\end_inset

.
 So the singular values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\sigma_{1} & 0\\
0 & \sigma_{2}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1=}\sqrt{200}=14.1421$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{2}=\sqrt{50}=7.0711$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, find the corresponding eigenvectors of its eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\,\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

, we denote them as 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\left[x_{1},\, x_{2}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\left[y_{1},\, y_{2}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(M-\lambda_{1}I)\, X=0\Rightarrow\left[\begin{array}{cc}
104-200 & -72\\
-72 & 146-200
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
x_{1}\\
x_{2}
\end{array}\right]=0\Rightarrow x_{1}=-\frac{3}{4}x_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}=1,$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=0.6,\, x_{2}=-0.8$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we can get 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0.8 & 0.6\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

.(Under the request that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 has the minimal number of signs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
X & Y\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0.6 & 0.8\\
-0.8 & 0.6
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $U=A(V^{*})^{-1}\Sigma^{-1}=AV\Sigma^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-2 & 11\\
-10 & 5
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0.6 & 0.8\\
-0.8 & 0.6
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
14.1421 & 0\\
0 & 7.0711
\end{array}\right]^{-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
thus 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-0.7071 & 0.7071\\
-0.7071 & -0.7071
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

