\begin_layout Description
Problem 5.4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the eigenvalues of the hermitian matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & A^{*}\\
A & 0
\end{array}\right]_{2m\times2m}$
\end_inset

 in block form are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\lambda_{(i-1)m+1} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{(i-1)m+2} & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & \lambda_{(i-1)m+m}
\end{array}\right]_{m\times m},\, i=1,2$
\end_inset

, and denote 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right]_{2m\times2m}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding eigenmatrix of the eigenvalues matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{1} & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,\, b,\, c\, d$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 block matrixs, then the eigenvalue decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M=X\Lambda X^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 So our goal is to find such 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and its corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is hermitian matrix, then by Theorem 5.5, the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 are real and the eigenmatrixs are unitary, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{-1}=X^{*},$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $M=X\Lambda X^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 To find 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

, we compute the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $det(M-\Lambda I)=0=det(\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-\lambda & A^{*}\\
A & -\lambda
\end{array}\right])\Rightarrow\lambda^{2}=\Sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=\Sigma\: and\,\lambda_{2}=-\Sigma$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\,\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 are both real.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we try to find 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We compute 
\begin_inset Formula $MM$
\end_inset

 separately.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U,\, V$
\end_inset

 are unitary
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
, so in one way, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MM=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & A^{*}\\
A & 0
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & A^{*}\\
A & 0
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
A^{*}A & 0\\
0 & AA^{*}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
V\Sigma^{2}V^{*} & 0\\
0 & U\Sigma{}^{2}U*
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the other way, since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is also unitary, so we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MM=(X\Lambda X^{*})(X\Lambda X^{*})=X\Lambda^{2}X^{*}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{1}^{2} & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2}^{2}
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
a^{*} & c^{*}\\
b^{*} & d^{*}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
a\Sigma^{2}a^{*}+b\Sigma^{2}b^{*} & a\Sigma^{2}c^{*}+b\Sigma^{2}d^{*}\\
c\Sigma^{2}a^{*}+d\Sigma^{2}b^{*} & c\Sigma^{2}c^{*}+d\Sigma^{2}d^{*}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
V\Sigma^{2}V^{*} & 0\\
0 & U\Sigma{}^{2}U*
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
a\Sigma^{2}a^{*}+b\Sigma^{2}b^{*} & a\Sigma^{2}c^{*}+b\Sigma^{2}d^{*}\\
c\Sigma^{2}a^{*}+d\Sigma^{2}b^{*} & c\Sigma^{2}c^{*}+d\Sigma^{2}d^{*}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow a\Sigma^{2}a^{*}+b\Sigma^{2}b^{*}=V\Sigma^{2}V^{*},\, a\Sigma^{2}c^{*}+b\Sigma^{2}d^{*}=0,\, c\Sigma^{2}a^{*}+d\Sigma^{2}b^{*}=0,\, c\Sigma^{2}c^{*}+d\Sigma^{2}d^{*}=U\Sigma{}^{2}U*$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is also a unitary matrix, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
a & c\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
b & d\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 are mutually orthogonal and their norms should be 1.
 So we find :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}V & \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}V\\
\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}U & -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}U
\end{array}\right]=\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
V & V\\
U & -U
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we get 
\begin_inset Formula $M=X\Lambda X^{-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Problem 6.3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathbb{C}^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

 is not a square matrix (suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $m>n$
\end_inset

), so we use the reduced singular value decomposition (SVD) of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\hat{U}\hat{\Sigma}V^{*}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}\in\mathbb{C}^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V\in\mathbb{C}^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 are both unitary and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Sigma}\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 is diagonal.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{*}A=(U\hat{\Sigma}V^{*})^{*}(U\hat{\Sigma}V^{*})=V\hat{\Sigma}^{2}V^{*}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Leftarrow\right):$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular, then 
\begin_inset Formula $det(A^{*}A)=det(V\hat{\Sigma}^{2}V^{*})=det(Vdet(\hat{\Sigma}^{2})det(V^{*})=det(\hat{\Sigma}^{2})\neq0$
\end_inset

, then all the n entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 are nonzero, which implies all of the n singular values of
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are nonzero, then
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is full rank.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Rightarrow\right):$
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is full rank, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has n nonzero singular values, then 
\begin_inset Formula $det(A^{*}A)=det(\hat{\Sigma}^{2})\neq0$
\end_inset

, so 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular.
 
\end_layout

